<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Sadly, Chinese Become
   Yesterday's Headlines
</HL>
<DATE>
05/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A13
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<LP>
   As I read the excerpt from Bette Bao Lord's book
"Legacies: A Chinese Mosaic" (editorial page, April 20), I
couldn't help wonder why the U.S. government -- and even
worse, the people of the U.S. -- continues to ignore the
oppression of human rights occurring in China. During the
Tiananmen Square incident, America rallied for the students
who craved a democratic society and protested the bloody
massacre that occurred afterward. It was obvious that as
journalists were expelled from the country and stories
stopped making the headlines, our concerns for the Chinese
people seemed to dwindle.
   We criticize countries for depriving their citizens
freedom of the press, stating they have a right to know what
is going on in the world. It is true that the nightly news
and newspaper media are a source of this information, but
should they have such an enormous control over such an
idealistic society as our own? One week it's China, the next
South Africa. And then the next week it's Lithuania. Let's
not lose sight of the fact that after the headlines are gone,
the problems still remain.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Valerie Saye
   Senior
   Middle Tennessee State University
   Murfreesboro, Tenn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900521-0131
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900521-0131.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   We Need Indexation
   To Control Inflation
</HL>
<DATE>
05/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A13
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<LP>
   Lindley H. Clark Jr.'s April 19 editorial-page column,
"Indexation May Be Bad for Us," implies that tax indexing
somehow increases the chances of high inflation. That's
absurd.
   An unindexed tax system gives politicians an incentive to
continue or increase inflation. At current inflation rates, a
repeal of tax indexing would increase taxes by $140 billion
over the next four years. Does anyone seriously believe that
the hidden tax increases caused by repeal of indexing would
end inflation? It certainly didn't work in the 1970s.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The politicians who create inflation would be the biggest
beneficiaries. After repealing indexing, politicians could
"cut" taxes by $100 billion over the four-year period, spend
the $40 billion difference on pet projects, and look like
heroes to their constituents.
   By taking the political profit out of inflation, tax
indexing helps control it. If there's an indexing culprit, it
is the indexation of congressional, high-ranking executive
branch and Federal Reserve officials' salaries. Consideration
should be given to rewarding the Federal Reserve officials
for low and steady rates of inflation.
   David Keating
   Executive Vice President
   National Taxpayers Union
   Washington
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900521-0130
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900521-0130.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   World Currency: Easier Said Than Done
</HL>
<DATE>
05/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A13
</SO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
</IN>
<LP>
   Warren E. Weber's otherwise excellent editorial-page
article, "America's Own Fixed-Exchange Model," April 26, has
the defect that it fosters confusion between two
fundamentally different monetary systems: a unified currency
and a system of national currencies linked to one another at
pegged exchange rates.
   A unified currency may have different names in different
places: during the heyday of the gold standard, a pound in
Britain, a dollar in the U.S.; currently, in the example used
by Mr. Weber, an A dollar, a B dollar for dollars issued by
different Federal Reserve districts.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The key feature that defines a unified currency is that
there is either no (the gold standard) or at most one (the
U.S. today) monetary authority authorized to issue fiat money
-- that is the translation of Mr. Weber's requirement that
there be "an agreement among countries about the amount of
seigniorage and its distribution." Stated differently, for a
fiat currency to be unified, there must be only one central
bank, though it can have any number of branches -- the U.S.
Federal Reserve System has 12. That requirement is easy to
state; it is exceedingly difficult to achieve on a world
scale. We shall, I predict, wait a long time before the U.S.,
Britain, Germany, France and Japan are all willing to convert
their national central banks into branches of a world central
bank -- and, I may say, as a U.S. citizen, I would be
extremely opposed to doing so.
   In the absence of the effective elimination of national
central banks, any "agreement among countries about the
amount of seigniorage and its distribution" will degenerate
into a Bretton Woods-pegged exchange-rate system, which would
inevitably break down as Bretton Woods did.
   Incidentally, a unified currency does not require or
involve literally fixed exchange rates. Before the Federal
Reserve System was established, the U.S. had a unified
currency internally, yet there was a market in St. Louis, to
take one example, for "New York dollars." The only reason
such markets do not exist currently is because the Federal
Reserve (i.e., the taxpayer) pays the transactions costs for
regional transfers of funds. Similarly, during the
gold-standard period, the exchange rate between the British
pound and the U.S. dollar varied within a range, the limits
of which were set by the costs of transporting gold to or
from Britain.
   A unified currency has many desirable features, but is not
at present a feasible alternative on any world-wide basis. A
system of national currencies linked by pegged exchange rates
has many undesirable features, yet it is a far more feasible
option under current circumstances.
   Milton Friedman
   Senior Research Fellow
   Hoover Institution
   Stanford, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900521-0129
</DOCNO>
