<LP>
   PHILADELPHIA -- Philadelphia Electric Co. appealed an
April 19 decision by the Pennsylvania Public Utility
Commission that granted the utility only $242.2 million of
the $548.6 million rate increase it requested.
   Philadelphia Electric said that by denying the rate
request, the commission unconstitutionally denied
shareholders any return on their investment in Limerick No. 2
nuclear power station. In denying most of the rate increase,
the commission disallowed the company's request to recover
the costs of building and operating the plant.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In the appeal, filed with the Commonwealth Court of
Pennsylvania, Philadelphia Electric alleged that the
commission approved various aspects of the project in the
mid-1980s, and then "suddenly reversed course" this year.
