   The following were among Friday's offerings and pricings
in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                        CORPORATES
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   European Investment Bank -- $300 million issue of 9 1/8%
notes, due June 1, 2002, won in competitive bidding by a
group led by First Boston Corp., priced at 99.32 to yield
9.22%. The noncallable notes were priced at a spread of 50
basis points above the Treasury's 10-year note. The issue is
rated Triple-A by both Moody's Investors Service Inc. and by
Standard &amp; Poor's Corp.
   Federal Farm Credit Banks -- $150 million of notes, due
June 5, 1992, priced at par to float weekly at a spread of 50
basis points above the Treasury's three-month bill. The
noncallable notes will be reoffered at various prices and
will pay interest quarterly.
   SunGard Data Systems Inc. -- $75 million of its 8 1/4%
convertible subordinate debentures due 2015 priced at par was
declared effective. The total principal amount of debentures
being sold was increased to $75 million from the $60 million
previously reported. The debentures will be convertible into
common stock at a price of $26 per share. Alex. Brown &amp; Sons
Inc. and First Boston Corp. are the underwriters.
                                                                                                       

                      MORTGAGE-BACKED
                                                                                                       

   Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. -- $400 million of Remic
mortgage securities is being offered in nine classes by
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. The offering, Series 177, is
backed by Freddie Mac 9% securities, with a weighted average
remaining term to maturity of 29.5 years.
   Ryland Mortgage Securities Corp. -- $100 million of
mortgage participation certificates (Series 1990-3), priced
Thursday. The issue, underwritten by Goldman Sachs &amp; Co.,
will be collateralized by fixed-rate mortgage loans purchased
from RAC Mortgage Funding Corp. Series 1990-3 will be
collateralized by mortgage loans having an initial aggregate
principal balance of approximately $30 million with original
and remaining terms to maturity of 15 years or less, and
mortgage loans having an initial aggregate principal balance
of approximately $70 million with original and remaining
terms to maturity of greater than 15 years but not more than
30 years. It is anticipated that Series 1990-3 will be rated
triple-A by both Moody's and S&amp;P. Ryland Mortgage Securities
Corp. is a limited-purpose finance subsidiary of Ryland
Acceptance Corp., which is an indirect, wholly owned
subsidiary of The Ryland Group Inc.
   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $300 million of
Remic mortgage securities, offered in 18 classes by Kidder
Peabody &amp; Co. The offering, Series 1990-68, is backed by
Fannie Mae 10% securities.
                                                                                                       

                           OTHER
                                                                                                       

   Province Of Newfoundland -- $150 million of 9 7/8%
debentures, due June 1, 2020, priced at 99.761 to yield
9.90%. The noncallable debentures were priced at a spread of
120 basis points above the Treasury's 30-year bellwether
bond. Rated Baa-1 by Moody's and single-A-minus by S&amp;P, the
issue will be sold through underwriters led by Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets.
                                                                                                       

