<HL>
   Coalition Pushes for Beer Companies
   To End Sponsorships of Motor Sports
   ----
   By Laurie McGinley
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6B
</SO>
<IN>
BEVERAGES (BVG)
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   Anti-drunk-driving activists want beer companies to
abandon their multimillion-dollar financing of car racing and
other motor sports, saying such sponsorships send the wrong
message.
   To bolster the case, the National Coalition to Prevent
Impaired Driving, a group of more than 100 traffic-safety and
public-health organizations, is holding a press conference
today to promote a new report, "Beer and Fast Cars: How
Brewers Target Blue-Collar Youth." The study concludes that
beer companies spend about $50 million a year "in a
sophisticated campaign to strengthen associations between
beer, cars and speed in a demographic group at elevated risk
of drinking and driving."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The coalition wants beer companies to drop their
motor-sports sponsorships voluntarily, and non-brewers to
pick up the sponsorships. If the brewers don't move, the
groups vow to campaign for a legislative ban.
   The attack is the latest public-relations headache for an
industry that in recent years has come under increasing
criticism for allegedly targeting young people, blacks and
Hispanics. James Sanders, president of the Beer Institute, a
trade association, calls the groups' complaint "ridiculous."
He says it "reached an absurd level that defies common
sense."
   But the report's author, David Buchanan, an assistant
professor at the University of Massachusetts school of public
health, contends that the beer industry, faced with declining
consumption by health-conscious, white-collar Americans, is
targeting blue-collar youth involved in the car culture.
"This target group is accurately perceived by the industry to
include the largest number of heavy beer drinkers," he says.
   At the same time, Prof. Buchanan says, young males from
blue-collar backgrounds are at disproportionately higher risk
of being killed in alcohol-related crashes.
   The report, financed by the AAA Foundation for Traffic
Safety and produced by California's Marin Institute, a
nonprofit research and advocacy group, finds that motor
sports, which include drag racing, motorcycle racing and
"monster-truck" competitions, receive more sponsorship money
from the beer industry than any other type of sport.
   "Beer companies are saturating motor events," says Michael
Schriefer, a pro race-car driver from Manhattan Beach, Calif.
"It's giving the young the wrong impression."
   Typically, motor-sport events are festooned with banners,
bunting and posters decorated with the name of the beer
sponsor, and feature several beer-dispensing booths. Some
events have emcees who periodically urge spectators to buy
beer. Beer companies sometimes underwrite an entire event,
and other times sponsor individual teams or drivers.
   Randi Lynn Hubbard, one of the few female monster-truck
drivers in the U.S., says there is so much beer consumed at
some events that she worries about the fans getting home
safely.
   The report recommends that if an outright ban on beer
sponsorships is politically unfeasible, other steps should be
taken, such as limiting the cup size for beer sales to 12
ounces and halting sales at least one hour before an event
ends.
   In reply, Stephen Burrows, vice president for consumer
awareness at Anheuser-Busch Cos., calls the report
"pseudoscience" based on opinion, not fact.
   "We've determined that racing is a good place to reach our
audience, which is adults over 21," Mr. Burrows says. He adds
that "to conclude that people who wear blue jeans and go to
racing events are drunk drivers is an insult to people who
enjoy racing events." Moreover, he notes that Anheuser-Busch
has spent millions on its "Know When to Say When" ad
campaign, designed to foster responsibility among the
consuming public.
   None of that is likely to mollify critics who argue that
the industry is targeting specific segments of society that
may be more vulnerable to alcohol abuse than others.
   Spring break, for example, remains a controversy. At
Texas's South Padre Island, a favorite gathering spot for
college students, the beer companies this year "weren't
handing out beer, but they had displays, and they sponsored
all kinds of beach games," says Bobby Heard, a spokesman for
Texans' War on Drugs, which is headquartered in Austin. "We
don't want them involved in spring break at all."
   Pat Taylor, director of the alcohol policies project at
the Center for Science in the Public Interest, says beer
companies should be banned from sponsoring rockband tours
because of their potential appeal to young people. She's also
concerned about malt-liquor advertising targeted to blacks
and Hispanics.
   Beer-industry officials say such concerns are misguided.
"No studies have ever related these marketing or advertising
activities to an increase or decrease in alcohol abuse," says
the Beer Institute's Mr. Sanders. Rather, executives say,
these marketing tools promote a specific product among
consumers who already have decided to drink.
   Brewers say the criticism of the industry's marketing
techniques comes from a group of activists who have a
paternalistic attitude toward the rest of the country. "We
believe the American public is smarter than these groups give
them credit for," says Anheuser-Busch's Mr. Burrows.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900521-0077
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900521-0077.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Enterprise -- The Fortress Companies:
   FAO Schwarz Is
   Back on Track
   With New Crew
   ----
   By Udayan Gupta
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<IN>
CORPORATE PROFILE (PRO)
SPECIALTY RETAILERS (OTS)
</IN>
<LP>
   {Last of a Series}
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   NEW YORK -- Five years ago, the famous toy seller FAO
Schwarz seemed like a derailed toy train.
   Sure enough, the company still offered $7,000 rocking
horses and $14,000 toy Lamborghinis. But the electronic toys
and Cabbage Patch dolls that sold big were nowhere to be
found. Long the nation's most prestigious toy seller to the
carriage trade, FAO Schwarz was becoming insignificant.
   But new owners, who purchased the company in 1985, have
revived this fortress under siege. When many companies begin
to stumble, they find failure isn't far away. But as the FAO
Schwarz experience shows, a company that is a fortress in its
marketplace often has such institutional strength that it can
recover from trouble -- at least, if owners are willing to
make big changes.
   The toy-store chain has revised its product mix, appealed
to a broader audience and started an aggressive merchandising
program. Toy industry analysts say sales tripled to about $60
million annually, from $20 million in 1984. The company
doesn't release sales and earnings figures. But it says the
chain -- which was losing money five years ago -- is again
profitable.
   "Of all the names people have tried to bring back from the
dead, FAO has been the most successful," declares Carol
Farmer, a retailing-industry consultant based in Boca Raton,
Fla. "It's remarkable what experienced managers and an
entrepreneurial spirit can do to a tradition-bound company."
   For all its recent problems, the company once seemed to
enjoy an impregnable position in its market niche. Tracing
its history to Civil War days, the company offered childhood
excitement to generations of Americans, especially if they
were rich. Visiting the company's flagship store on Fifth
Avenue here was "like dying and going to heaven," recalls New
York venture capitalist Edwin Goodman. As a child, he says he
stood mesmerized for hours in front of the elaborate Lionel
train display, watching the trains meander through the
mountains and the forests. "It was absolutely hypnotic," Mr.
Goodman says.
   At least one out-of-town five-year-old was so excited by
his first visit to the store that he fainted, recalls F.A.O.
(Fritz) Schwarz Jr., a New York lawyer.
   His great grandfather, Frederick August Otto Schwarz, an
immigrant from Germany, opened the first Schwarz store in
1862, in Baltimore. After running the company profitably for
over a century, the family sold it in 1963. "My father asked
if anyone wanted to run the stores, and no one did," says Mr.
Schwarz.
   The company lost strength under a series of owners, which
included Parents Magazine Inc. and W.R. Grace &amp; Co.
   At one point, for instance, the company concentrated on
stocking the store with expensive European-made toys, which
alienated domestic toy makers, industry executives say. And
when the industry boomed in the early 1980s because of such
new products as the Cabbage Patch Kids, FAO Schwarz refused
to carry them because they didn't fit its high-end image.
   By the early 1980s, the entire chain was suffering. Big
discounters such as Toys 'R' Us Inc. and mass marketers like
K mart Corp. and Wal-Mart Stores dominated toy retailing.
With a policy of stocking only expensive items, FAO Schwarz
found itself ignored by consumers.
   Many U.S. manufacturers routinely left FAO out of their
marketing plans. "We didn't care if we sold to them or not,"
says Herbert Raiffe, president of Gund Inc., an Edison, N.J.,
toy maker.
   Even the store concedes its decline was creating a
depressing atmosphere. Peter Harris, now FAO Schwarz's chief
executive, says: "FAO had become a frightening kind of place.
It was scaring away customers." Mr. Harris, who had managed
the chain for a previous owner, acquired it in 1985, in
partnership with Philadelphia investment banker Peter Morse
and several FAO Schwarz employees.
   The new owners brought in new capital and new directors
familiar with upscale retailing. Late in 1987, they raised
about $7 million in capital from Prudential Venture Partners,
New York, and Boston's Charles River Ventures. They expanded
the board to include Tiffany &amp; Co. Chairman William Chaney;
Lew Frankfort, president of Coach Leatherware, and venture
capitalist Paul Hirschbiel of Prudential.
   But the hard part was "to find a way to redeliver to
customers' expectations," Mr. Harris says. To the partners
that meant redefining the store's entire philosophy: Keeping
the upscale image but expanding it to include new generations
of customers. "We weren't competing for the customer that
shops at Toys 'R' Us or Wal-Mart. We're looking for an
upscale buyer of gifts," says Mr. Harris.
   The company is emphasizing convenience over price by
providing new services. These include a "two-minute shop"
that offers pre-wrapped toys for quick shopping, free
gift-wrapping and a personal shopping service both for phone
customers and in-store shoppers. Customers who can't make
regular shopping hours can arrange visits at other times.
   The company also stocks a broader range of products,
including more toys than before in the $15 to $25 range. The
store isn't abandoning its policy of selling $225 rocking
bluebirds or $295 table soccer sets; it's merely casting a
wider net for customers, explains Mr. Harris.
   As part of its new merchandising strategy, FAO Schwarz
once again is courting big U.S. toy makers like Hasbro Inc.
and Tyco Toys Inc.
   There's now an open-door policy for the smaller and less
heralded toy makers: They can visit during working hours and
be guaranteed a meeting with one of the store's buyers. "We
want to act as a showcase for smaller entrepreneurial
companies," says Mr. Harris.
   Last November, FAO Schwarz helped launch Magnetic
Dimensions, an interactive, three-dimensional toy marketed by
Sicommerce Inc., New York, with a party for 5,000 guests. It
also devoted an exclusive display area and space to play with
the product. In the first eight weeks, the store sold 5,000
units at $50 each, says Robert Lieberman, vice president of
Sicommerce. "They launched the product and they made us a
star."
   The flagship store itself, moved to a new location in
1987, also underwent a major transformation. Shoppers,
greeted by doormen dressed as toy soldiers, walk into a space
dwarfed by a 28-foot tall, electronic animated musical clock.
The surrounding space is filled with hundreds of plush
animals, some gigantic, some dwarf-like. A cage-like glass
elevator or a child-friendly slow-moving escalator takes
shoppers to the second floor where children can lounge about
and construct their Lego sets or watch transfixed as the
trains go by.
   "The {New York} store is fresher than it's ever been,"
says Alan Hassenfeld, chairman and chief executive of Hasbro,
the nation's largest toy company.
   Though the new owners have trimmed the chain to 15 stores
from 22 five years ago, they have opened a new store in San
Francisco and plan additional stores in Chicago and Tokyo.
They also have revived their catalog and plan to mail it to
over five million customers this year.
   As in the early days of the store, Mr. Hassenfeld
declares, "it's once again the place where things happen."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900521-0076
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900521-0076.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Hubble Telescope Shows Signs of Promise
   As First Pictures of Universe Come Back
   ----
   By Bob Davis
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6E
</SO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   GREENBELT, Md. -- The Hubble Space Telescope took its
first photos of the universe, ending fears that it was
becoming a space turkey and offering hope that it may become
the space masterpiece promised instead.
   The orbiting telescope has been plagued by software
problems, jittery hardware and human error since it was
launched April 24. But yesterday, it aimed its main camera at
a nearby star cluster, known as NGC 3532, and relayed back
some striking shots. The space telescope was able to discern
that an image, which looked like an oblong blob in a photo
taken recently by a big telescope in Chile, was instead two
stars orbiting near each other.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "This is as good or better than {images} I've seen at Mt.
Palomar," said James Westphal, the Hubble astronomer in
charge of the camera, referring to the big California
observatory.
   But the telescope -- at about $2.5 billion, the most
expensive spacecraft ever built -- still must improve
significantly to reach the ambitious goals set out for it by
the National Aeronautics and Space Administration. Space
agency officials have bragged that the telescope will be able
to pinpoint objects 25 times dimmer than those seen from
Earth and see back nearly to the time of the Big Bang.
Astronomers want to use that power to measure the age of the
universe more precisely and to search for such exotic
phenomena as black holes -- gravitational masses that swallow
any stars unfortunate enough to be in the way.
   But before it starts those searches, NASA must upgrade the
telescope's focus by a factor of seven, Hubble scientists
said, and reduce the telescope's jitters by a factor of 10.
NASA has plans to accomplish both, and expects to start using
the telescope for scientific exploration in about 2 1/2
months.
   Yesterday was a kind of christening for the telescope,
which astronomers call "first light." It was the first time
the telescope was used to record and transmit images to the
ground; it was also a test of how well the telescope is able
to focus using relatively coarse adjustments. With first
light, said Duccio Macchetto, one of the telescope's
principal scientists, "You know you have something that
works."
   Hubble scientists and the press congregated around video
monitors at NASA's Goddard Space Flight Center, which
controls the spacecraft from the ground. All the scientists
professed confidence in the telescope, but as first light
arrived, their bravura faded.
   "Oh damn, I can't see from here," snapped John Bahcall, a
grey-haired astronomer wearing Reeboks who lobbied NASA and
Congress for years to build the telescope. After changing his
seat, he sat transfixed as the images appeared on the screen.
Edward Weiler, another Hubble veteran, rolled his tongue
compulsively, and called over to Mr. Bahcall: "We're almost
there, John."
   The screen showed Mr. Westphal, an elfin man with a white
crew-cut and white beard, working on the images at a computer
terminal with two assistants elsewhere at Goddard. When it
became clear that the pictures were twice as good as
expected, tension turned to good cheer.
   Afterwards, Mr. Bahcall congratulated Jean Olivier, the
NASA official in charge of the test, and speculated that Mr.
Olivier may have underestimated how well the telescope would
perform to make the results look better. Both he and Mr.
Oliver hail from Shreveport, La., Mr. Bahcall said, and
"That's the way we Louisiana boys do it."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900521-0075
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900521-0075.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Lotus-Novell
   Plan for Merger
   Is Called Off
   ---
   Collapse of $1.5 Billion Deal
   Adds to Growing Power
   Of Dominant Microsoft
   ----
   By John R. Wilke
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   LOTS NOVL MSFT
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
SOFTWARE (SOF)
</IN>
<LP>
   Lotus Development Corp.'s $1.5 billion merger with Novell
Inc. collapsed at the 11th hour, eliminating a potential
challenge to the growing dominance of software industry
leader Microsoft Corp.
   The combination, announced April 6, had been hailed as
redrawing the balance of power in the booming
personal-computer software business. Analysts said at the
time that the planned merger provided a counterweight to the
power of Microsoft, Redmond, Wash. The deal's collapse leaves
Microsoft more dominant than ever and gives its two most
important challengers self-inflicted wounds.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Lotus's chairman and chief executive officer, Jim P.
Manzi, said in an interview that negotiations with Novell
fell apart late Friday, after Provo, Utah-based Novell's
board unexpectedly demanded that the new company's board be
made up of four directors each from Novel and Lotus, which is
based in Cambridge, Mass. Lotus, which had already made major
concessions to Novell to stregthen Novell's voice in
management, rejected the new proposal.
   Mr. Manzi seemed stung by the sudden reversal. After all,
he said, Novell's chairman had first proposed the merger.
"It's a shame," Mr. Manzi said. "We ended up wasting a lot of
time and money talking with people who apparently didn't know
what they wanted."
   Novell's version of the events couldn't be determined.
Raymond Noorda, Novell's chairman, president and chief
executive, was unavailable yesterday, a spokeswoman for him
said. She said the company's executives wouldn't have any
comment until today.
   Analysts said the failure of the two companies to come to
terms is likely to lead to other partnerships. "This sets the
stage for a realignment of the software industry," Rick
Sherlund, an analyst with Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co., said.
   In a letter of intent signed April 5, Lotus and Novell
spelled out a four-three board with four directors from
Lotus, and designated Mr. Noorda vice chairman. Novell was to
be acquired through a stock swap of 1.19131 Lotus shares for
each Novell share.
   But investors at first reacted negatively to the proposed
deal, and Novell holders were unhappy that it didn't offer
them a premium for their shares. Critics also raised
questions about whether the companies' technologies and
sharply different management cultures could be combined.
Indeed, analysts said institutional holders of Novell may
have pressured board members to alter terms of the deal.
   Mr. Manzi said that in subsequent negotiations, Lotus had
agreed to make Mr. Noorda chairman of the combined companies,
with Mr. Manzi serving as president and chief executive, and
agreed to rename the company Lotus/Novell Corp. The revised
terms, meant to ensure a strong management role for Mr.
Noorda, were agreed upon Wednesday, Mr. Manzi said. He was so
sure the merger would go through that he left with his family
Thursday for a weekend vacation at Walt Disney World in
Orlando, Fla. "We thought we had a deal," he said.
   But Novell's board met Friday and demanded that the
composition of the board be changed, Mr. Manzi said. "They
had repeatedly agreed to the four-three board, and we weren't
going to give in on this," he said. "A four-four board is a
prescription for deadlock."
   The combined companies would have had revenue of more than
$1 billion, surpassing that of Microsoft and dominating their
respective markets. Lotus has long been the leader in
financial spreadsheet software with its best-selling 1-2-3
line, while Novell holds an estimated 60% market share in
network operating systems, the software that weaves
stand-alone personal computers into networks.
   Analysts said the broken deal marks a major setback for
both companies, and leaves Microsoft in an even stronger
position on the eve of one of the largest product
announcements in its history. Microsoft tomorrow will
announce Windows 3.0, a strategic enhancement of its flagship
operating-system software package known as MS-DOS, the basic
operating software that controls most personal computers.
   In the wake of the failed merger, "Microsoft emerges as
the big winner," said Mr. Sherlund of Goldman Sachs. Lotus
and Novell "have cast their future," he said. "It's likely to
be tougher for both of them -- and a lot easier for
Microsoft."
   Analysts also said the collapse leaves open the
possibility that Novell will seek other partners. "They've
been down that road once, maybe they are willing to try
again," said David Readerman of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
He didn't speculate on other potential partners.
   The collapse of the deal led to speculation that another
suitor had emerged for Novell. But Mr. Manzi dismissed this
possibility and added that there was a no-shop clause in the
letter of intent, precluding Novell from seeking other
partners during negotiations.
   Nonetheless, some Novell investors began accumulating
shares last week, betting that the deal would be broken and
that a richer one might be forthcoming, said Robert Therrien,
an analyst with PaineWebber Inc.
   The merger's failure raises anew all of the long-term
strategic concerns that brought the two companies together.
With Microsoft in control of the basic software that runs
personal computers, nearly every other company in the
industry must tailor their products to work with those of
Microsoft. The company's lengthening shadow led one industry
executive to call it "the Standard Oil of the software
industry."
   "Those concerns aren't going away," Mr. Sherlund of
Goldman Sachs said. "And it's going to be very awkward for
Novell and Lotus to go back to shareholders and tell them
that the compelling need they saw for this merger last month
is no longer so pressing."
   In national over-the-counter trading Friday, Lotus shares
closed at $34.375, unchanged, and Novell shares closed at
$40.125, up 12.5 cents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
