<HL>
   California Court Rejects
   Fetal-Protection Policy
</HL>
<DATE>
05/21/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   JCI LABOR
</CO>
<IN>
AUTO PARTS AND EQUIPMENT INCLUDING TIRES (AUP)
</IN>
<LP>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- (AP) Women can't be banned from jobs that
could harm a fetus, California's highest court ruled,
upholding a challenge to a company policy that affected even
women who have no plans to have children.
   The state Supreme Court on Thursday let stand a lower
court ruling that a battery company's fetal-protection
policy, keeping fertile women away from jobs that could
expose them to low levels of lead, amounts to sex
discrimination.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The company, Milwaukee-based Johnson Controls Inc., also
has a case pending before the U.S. Supreme Court over the
same policy.
   The California appellate decision had called the policy
"blatant, overt gender-based discrimination" based on
"unfounded, unscientific stereotypic notions about women."
   "We are in an era of choice. A woman is not required to
become a Victorian brood mare," said the 4th District Court
of Appeal in its 3-0 ruling Feb. 28 in a case from Fullerton.
   But in a case stemming from a Johnson Controls plant in
Minnesota, a federal appeals court had upheld the policy. The
U.S. Supreme Court is expected to rule on the issue by
mid-1991.
   However that turns out, Thursday's action, involving state
fair-employment law, should settle the issue for California,
a state lawyer said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
